This is a good topic. Thank you &quot;someone&quot; for posting it!<br><br>
For a Vietnam Veteran, like myself, I feel &quot;character&quot; includes the following:<br><br>
1. Dealing with youself and everyone else honestly, even if it hurts.<br><br>
2. Standing your ground for honorable principles, what is right.<br><br>
3. Conducting your life in ways that have meaning for you and those around you.<br><br>
4. Treating people with respect and dignity.<br><br>
5. Caring for yourself first, so you can really care for others in a meaningful way.<br><br>
6. Making the effort to fix yourself, and to ask for help, when you realize you are messed up.<br><br>
7. Not personally being a dishrag or a doormat.<br><br>
Once a Vietnam Vet, always a Vietnam Vet! That will follow all of us to our graves, and I can say it with pride.<br><br>
Once, a while back, a CO for whom I have the greatest respect and admiration, told me he felt that the Vietnam Veteran was a window to the soul of the American People. I think this is part of our character, too. <br><br>
